    bio: "Abu Abdullah Muhammad ibn Battuta was born in Tangier, Morocco, in 1304 into a family of Islamic legal scholars. At the age of twenty-one, he set out on the hajj to Mecca — a journey that would stretch into nearly three decades of almost continuous travel across the known world. By the time he returned home for good, he had visited the equivalent of more than forty modern nations, covering an estimated 75,000 miles, a distance unmatched by any known traveler until the age of steam.\n\nIbn Battuta's journeys took him from the courts of West African kings to the steppes of Central Asia, from the Malabar Coast of India to the islands of Southeast Asia and possibly the coast of China. He served as a qadi — an Islamic judge — in the Sultanate of Delhi for several years, survived shipwrecks, encountered the Black Death sweeping through Syria, and navigated the political intrigues of dozens of rulers eager to employ a well-traveled scholar. His observations on trade routes, religious practices, architectural wonders, and local customs provide an irreplaceable window into the fourteenth-century Islamic world and the civilizations at its edges.\n\nUpon his final return to Morocco around 1354, Sultan Abu Inan Faris commissioned the young scholar Ibn Juzayy to compile Ibn Battuta's oral accounts into a written work known as the Rihla, meaning \"The Journey.\" Though some modern historians question certain claims — particularly regarding his supposed visit to China — the Rihla remains one of the most important travel documents in human history. Ibn Battuta died in Morocco around 1368, largely forgotten for centuries until European scholars rediscovered his work in the nineteenth century and recognized him as one of the greatest explorers who ever lived."
